  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction:</title>
    <aside>
      <p>
        If we remove the restriction that <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> have to be integers,
        this problem becomes a lot more interesting.
      </p>
      <p>
        It can be shown that for any value <m>N > { e}^{ e}</m>,
        there exist real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> that satisfy
        <m>N = a^b = b^a</m> with <m>a \neq b</m>.
        To prove this,
        one needs to be very careful in evaluating the limit
        <me>
          \lim_{\substack{a \rightarrow 1\\ b \rightarrow \infty} } a^b
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        It is not obvious that this limit goes to infinity.
        However, if it does,
        all <m>N > { e}^{ e}</m> will have the desired property.
        It may help to recall that
        <me>
          \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left(1 + \frac{1}{n} \right)^n = { e}
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        So, just because the base tends to <m>1</m> and the exponent tends to infinity,
        the value of <m>a^b</m> is not necessarily infinity.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <p>
          <idx><h>limit</h></idx>
          <idx><h>limit</h><h>at infinity</h></idx>
          <idx><h>limit</h><h>definition of e</h></idx>
    </p>
    <p>
      We all know that <m>16</m> exhibits the following interesting property:
      <me>
        16 = 2^4 = 4^2
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Are there any other positive integers <m>N</m> for which there exist positive integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> (<m>a \not = b</m>) such that
      <me>
        N = a^b = b^a?
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      This activity will explore this question.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises:</title>
    <p>
      Let's assume that for some <m>N \not = 16</m>,
      there are positive integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>N = a^b = b^a</m>.
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>a^b = b^a</m>, can we solve for <m>a</m> or <m>b</m>?
            Why or why not?
            Try to do this by hand and comment on the result in a new paragraph.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Rearrange the equation to separate the <m>a</m>'s and <m>b</m>'s, so that all <m>a</m>'s are on one side and all <m>b</m>'s are on the other side.
            Comment about what you notice about the left and right sides of the equation in a new paragraph.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Assign the function <m>f(x) = \ln(x)/x</m>.
            Graph <m>f(x)</m> using Maple.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Determine the critical point(s) and the maximum and minimum values
            (if they exist).
              <idx><h>shapes of curves</h><h>critical number</h></idx>
              <idx><h>shapes of curves</h><h>maximum</h></idx>
              <idx><h>shapes of curves</h><h>minimum</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Insert a new paragraph and comment on what happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>.
              <idx><h>shapes of curves</h><h>horizontal asymptote</h></idx>
              <idx><h>asymptote</h><h>horizontal</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            On what intervals is <m>f(x)</m> increasing and decreasing?
            Answer on a new paragraph.
              <idx><h>shapes of curves</h><h>increasing</h></idx>
              <idx><h>shapes of curves</h><h>decreasing</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>f(a) = f(b)</m> and <m>a \lt b</m>,
            what does that mean in terms of the graph?
            Answer on a new paragraph. (<em>Hint: Rolle's Theorem</em>)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>f(a) = f(b)</m> and <m>a \lt b</m>,
            prove that <m>a = 2</m> is the only positive integer such that <m>a^b = b^a</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Rolle's Theorem:</em>
          <idx><h>Rolle's theorem</h></idx>
      Let <m>f</m> be a function that satisfies the following three hypotheses:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f</m> is continuous on the closed interval <m>[a,b]</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f</m> is differentiable on the open interval <m>(a,b)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(a) = f(b)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      Then there is a number <m>c</m> in <m>(a,b)</m> such that <m>f'(c) = 0</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
